{{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy|21st-century philosophy]] |color = |image = |name = '''Sean D. Kirkland''' |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = [[Continental philosophy|Continental]] | institutions = [[DePaul University]] |main_interests = [[Ancient Greek Philosophy]], [[Phenomenology (philosophy)|Phenomenology]] |notable_ideas = | spouse = | education = | alma_mater = [[Stony Brook University]] |influences = [[Socrates]], [[Heidegger]] |influenced = |awards = [[Symposium Book Award]] }}
'''Sean D. Kirkland''' is an American philosopher and associate professor of [[philosophy]] at [[DePaul University]]. He is known for his expertise on [[Ancient Greek Philosophy]]. Kirkland won the 2013 [[Symposium Book Award]] for his monograph ''The Ontology of Socratic Questioning in Platos Early Dialogues''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Book Award|url=https://www.c-scp.org/symposium/symposium-book-award|website=[[The Canadian Society for Continental Philosophy]]|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Sean Kirkland|url=http://www.asage.org/index.php/ASAGE/article/download/148/73|website=American Society for Aesthetics Graduate E-journal|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref>
