{{other people||William Bryan (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox officeholder | name = William Lowe Bryan | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | order = 10th | title = President of the [[Indiana University]] | term_start = 1902 | term_end = 1937 | predecessor = [[Joseph Swain (academic)|Joseph Swain]] | successor = [[Herman B Wells]] | birth_name = <!-- if different from "name" --> | birth_date = {{birth date |1860|11|11}} | birth_place = [[Monroe County, Indiana]] | death_date = {{death date and age |1955|11|21|1860|11|11}} | death_place = [[Bloomington, Indiana]] | death_cause = | resting_place = [[Crown Hill Cemetery]] | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = US | spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )--> | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | footnotes = | module = {{Infobox academic | child=yes | alma_mater = {{ublist|[[Indiana University]]|[[Clark University]]}} | thesis_title = On the development of voluntary motor ability, with a preface on the requirements of work in experimental psychology | thesis_url = https://search.proquest.com/docview/301690426/ | thesis_year = 1892 | doctoral_advisor = [[G. Stanley Hall]] | academic_advisors = [[David Starr Jordan]] | influences = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | era = | discipline = [[Psychology]] | sub_discipline = | workplaces = [[Indiana University]] | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | main_interests = | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influenced = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> }} }}
[[File:College Avenue North 812, William Lowe Bryan House, Illinois and North College HD.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Bryan's house in Bloomington]] '''William Lowe Bryan''' (November 11, 1860 – November 21, 1955) was the 10th president of [[Indiana University]], serving from 1902 to 1937.<ref name="psych1988" />
==Early life and education== William Lowe Bryan was born William Julian Bryan on November 11, 1860 in [[Monroe County, Indiana]]. His father, John Bryan was a Presbyterian minister and his mother was Eliza Phillips Bryan. Having been born near [[Bloomington, Indiana|Bloomington]], Bryan graduated from IU with degrees in ancient [[classics]] and [[philosophy]]. His interests shifted toward [[psychology]] and Bryan went on to earn his Ph.D. in psychology from [[Clark University]] in 1892 under the direction of [[G. Stanley Hall]].<ref name="thesis-bryan-1892">{{cite thesis |url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/301690426/ |title=On the development of voluntary motor ability, with a preface on the requirements of work in experimental psychology |date=1892 |publisher=[[Clark University]] |type=Ph.D. |last=Bryan |first=William L. |via=[[ProQuest]] |subscription=yes |oclc=11645931}}</ref><ref name="psych1988">{{cite web |url=http://psych.indiana.edu/tradition/Hearst_and_Capshew_1988.pdf |title=Psychology at Indiana University: A centennial review And compendium |editor-first1=Eliot |editor-last1=Hearst |editor-first2=James H. |editor-last2=Capshew |year=1988 |publisher=Indiana University Department of Psychology}}</ref>
==Achievements== That same year Bryan helped organize the [[American Psychological Association]] and became one of its charter members. He returned to IU in 1893 to accept a professorship in the psychology department and the appointment to vice president of the university. He succeeded [[Joseph Swain (academic)|Joseph Swain]] as president in 1902 and led the institution for 35 years until 1937, at which time he retired as president emeritus at the age of 76.
Bryan presided over the transformation of IU from a small, traditional liberal arts college into a modern research university. His most notable accomplishment was the expansion of graduate and professional training. During his administration, schools or departments of medicine, education, journalism, nursing, business, music, and dentistry were established.<ref name="psych1988" />
One of the early challenges of Bryan's presidency was providing the university campus with a sufficient amount of water for its operation. (Bloomington, and the IU campus in particular, is located on a high ground without any major rivers or lakes in the vicinity, and with little usable [[groundwater]]).<ref name=maxwell>{{cite journal |first=Donald H. |last=Maxwell |title=Impounded water in Bloomington, Ind. |pages=159–161 |journal=Municipal and county engineering: design, construction, maintenance, and operation of all public works |volume=60 |issue=1 |date=January 1921|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1ZRNAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA160 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> The city's waterworks existing in the early 20th century being utterly inadequate, Bryan commissioned a team of IU researchers, led by the geologist E.R. Cumings, to investigate the campus' water situation. On March 8, 1910, the Cumings commission recommended a site for the new reservoir, a couple miles northeast of the campus; the reservoir, which became known as the [[Griffy Lake#University Lake|University Lake]], was constructed in 1910-1914.<ref name=cravens>{{cite news |first=John W. |last=Cravens |title=Buildings on the old and new campuses of Indiana University |magazine=Indiana University Alumni Quarterly |volume=9 |year=1922 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vAITAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA318 |pages=317–319 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Although no longer used for water supply, the reservoir remains, and is the centerpiece of Indiana University's Research and Teaching Preserve (Griffy Woods).<ref name=sahu>{{cite web |title=Indiana University Griffy Lake Watershed: Sustainability Survey |first=Neil |last=Sahu |year=2008 |url=http://www.indiana.edu/~sustain/docs/sinterns_08/sahu_report.pdf}}</ref>
William Lowe Bryan died in Bloomington in 1955.<ref name="cdt-1955nov22">{{cite news |title=Dr. Bryan dies; Retired head of Indiana U.; Directed Expansion of University |newspaper=[[Chicago Daily Tribune]] |date=November 22, 1955 |page=a10 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://chicagotribune.newspapers.com/newspage/372352192/ |subscription=yes |quote=Dr. William Lowe Bryan, 95, president emeritus of Indiana University died here today in his home on the university campus.}} [https://search.proquest.com/docview/179610743/ Alternate Link] via [[ProQuest]].</ref> He was buried next to his wife at [[Crown Hill Cemetery]] in [[Indianapolis]].<ref name="is-1955nov24">{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/105583630/ |title=Dr. Bryan's Story Read At Rites |newspaper=[[Indianapolis Star]] |date=November 24, 1955 |page=25 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |subscription=yes |quote=Dr. William Lowe Bryan, 95-year-old president emeritus of Indiana University, was buried beside the body of his wife in simple graveside services at Crown Hill yesterday}}</ref>
